The software package ACE-ilProlog is freely available for scientific
(non-commercial) use.  It belongs to the Computer Science Department
of the K.U.Leuven.  The following terms cover the use of the software
package:

1. The package ACE-ilProlog can be used only for the purpose of
internal research excluding any commercial use of the package
ACE-ilProlog as such or as a part of a software product.

2. K.U.Leuven, Department of Computer Science shall for all purposes
be considered the owner of ACE-ilProlog and of all copyright, trade
secret, patent or other intellectual property rights therein.
K.U.Leuven has granted an exclusive license for the commercial
exploitation of ACE-ilProlog to PharmaDM (discovery@PharmaDM.com).

3. The package ACE-ilProlog is provided on an "as is" basis and for
the purpose described in paragraph 1 only.  In no circumstances can
K.U.Leuven be held liable for any deficiency, fault or other
mishappening with regard to the use or performance of the package
ACE-ilProlog.

4. All scientific publications, for which the package ACE-ilProlog has
been used, shall mention usage of the package ACE-ilProlog, and shall
refer to the following publication:
        H. Blockeel, L. Dehaspe, B. Demoen, G. Janssens, J. Ramon, and 
        H. Vandecasteele, Executing query packs in ILP, 
        Inductive Logic Programming, 10th International Conference, ILP2000, 
        London, UK, July 2000, Proceedings (J. Cussens and A. Frisch, eds.), 
        Lecture Notes in Artificial Intelligence, vol. 1866, Springer,
        2000, pp. 60-77. 


In addition, the following references to publications describing
algorithms available within the package ACE-ilProlog shall be included
where relevant:

  - Tilde (for classification):
  H. Blockeel, and L. De Raedt, Top-down induction of first-order logical
  decision trees, Artificial Intelligence 101 (1998), no. 1-2, 285-297.

  - Tilde (for clustering or regression):
  H. Blockeel, L. De Raedt, and J. Ramon, Top-down induction of clustering
  trees, Proceedings of the 15th International Conference on Machine
  Learning (J. Shavlik, ed.), Morgan Kaufmann, 1998, pp. 55-63.

  - Warmr:
  L. Dehaspe, and H. Toivonen, Discovery of frequent Datalog patterns,
  Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery 3 (1999), no. 1, 7-36.

